      • contains

        public final boolean contains(String string)
        Description copied from interface: Container
        Check the existence of some give string based term with prolog syntax in this Container. The string based term will be parsed and the internal term representation query to the prolog engine. The contention concept is base on the prolog clause/2 built-in on instance prolog engine. The clause/2 check that exist some clause in the prolog program or database which unifies your head and your body. The clause/2 is based on terms unification and make more flexible the contention concept. If clause/2 success then in the prolog program/database some define clause match with converted object and can be resolved. If clause/2 fail then in the prolog program/database no one clause exist that resolve the converted object. 
         objectContainer.contains("'io.github.prolobjectlink.domain.geometry.Point'(Idp, X, Y)");
 objectContainer.contains("'io.github.prolobjectlink.domain.geometry.Point'( a, 3,14 )");
        Formulated Prolog Query 
         ?- clause('io.github.prolobjectlink.domain.geometry.Point'( Idp, X, Y ),true).
 ?- clause('io.github.prolobjectlink.domain.geometry.Point'( a, 3,14 ),true).
        Specified by:
        contains in interface Container
        Parameters:
        string - string based prolog term.
        Returns:
        true if string based term is defined in this Container, false otherwise.
        See Also:
        Container.contains(Object), Container.contains(Class), Container.contains(Predicate), Container.contains(String, int)

        public final <O> boolean contains(O object)
        Description copied from interface: Container
        Check the existence of some give object in this Container. The object will be converted with ObjectFactory to equivalent prolog term and query to the prolog engine. The contention concept is base on the prolog clause/2 built-in on instance prolog engine. The clause/2 check that exist some clause in the prolog program or database which unifies your head and your body. The clause/2 is based on terms unification and make more flexible the contention concept. If clause/2 success then in the prolog program/database some define clause match with converted object and can be resolved. If clause/2 fail then in the prolog program/database no one clause exist that resolve the converted object. 
         objectContainer.contains(new Point("a", 3, 14));
        Formulated Prolog Query 
         ?- clause('io.github.prolobjectlink.domain.geometry.Point'( a, 3,14 ),true).
        Specified by:

      • contains

        public final <O> boolean contains(Class<O> clazz)
        Description copied from interface: Container
        Check the existence of some give class in this Container. The class will be converted with ObjectConverter to equivalent prolog term and query to the prolog engine. The equivalent prolog term is the most general predicate that represent a relation in prolog context. The contention concept is base on the prolog clause/2 built-in on instance prolog engine. The clause/2 check that exist some clause in the prolog program or database which unifies your head and your body. The clause/2 is based on terms unification and make more flexible the contention concept. If clause/2 success then in the prolog program/database some define clause match with converted object and can be resolved. If clause/2 fail then in the prolog program/database no one clause exist that resolve the converted object. 
         objectContainer.contains(Point.class);
        Formulated Prolog Query 
         ?- clause('io.github.prolobjectlink.domain.geometry.Point'( Idp, X, Y ),true).
        Specified by:
        contains in interface Container
        Type Parameters:
        O - type to be converted to equivalent prolog term and querying to the prolog engine.
        Parameters:
        clazz - class to be converted to equivalent prolog term and querying to the prolog engine.
        Returns:
        true if the converted class to prolog term is defined in this Container, false otherwise.
        See Also:
        Container.contains(String), Container.contains(Object), Container.contains(Predicate), Container.contains(String, int)

      • contains

        public final boolean contains(String functor,
                              int arity)
        Description copied from interface: Container
        Check the existence of prolog predicates in this Container that have predicate indicator created from the given functor and arity. The contention concept is base on the prolog current_predicate/1 built-in on instanced prolog engine. The current_predicate/1 check that exist some predicate in the prolog program/database or engine defined built-ins with equals functor and arity. If current_predicate/1 success then in the prolog program/database or engine defined built-ins some define predicate match with the given functor and arity and can be resolved. If current_predicate/1 fail then in the prolog program/database or engine defined built-ins no one predicate exist.
        Specified by:
        contains in interface Container
        Parameters:
        functor - predicate functor
        arity - predicate arity
        Returns:
        true if in the program/database or engine built-ins held by this Container is defined at least one predicate with predicate indicator created from the given functor and arity , false otherwise.
        See Also:
        Container.contains(Class), Container.contains(String), Container.contains(Object), Container.contains(Predicate)
